4.2. Comprehensive Threat Model and Countermeasures

•
Mandate: Develop a comprehensive threat model for the cloud IDE, detailing high-risk attack vectors and their specific countermeasures. This must include:

•
Threat Model - Sandbox Escape: A detailed threat model for sandbox escape attempts, where a malicious user attempts to break out of the isolated execution environment. Detail countermeasures such as kernel-level isolation (Firecracker, gVisor), syscall filtering (seccomp-bpf), memory randomization, and continuous monitoring for suspicious system calls.

•
Threat Model - Privilege Escalation via Plugin Ecosystem: A detailed threat model for privilege escalation through malicious or vulnerable plugins. Detail countermeasures such as strict capability-based security for plugins, granular permissions, runtime monitoring of plugin behavior, and automated detection of unauthorized resource access.

•
Threat Model - Code Injection in Live Preview: A detailed threat model for code injection attacks targeting the live preview environment (e.g., XSS, HTML injection). Detail countermeasures such as strict content security policies (CSPs), input sanitization, output encoding, and isolated rendering contexts.

•
Threat Model - Version Control System Tampering: A detailed threat model for tampering with the integrated version control system (e.g., Git repository). Detail countermeasures such as cryptographic signing of commits, multi-factor authentication for repository access, and continuous integrity checks of repository data.

•
Threat Model - Malformed Payloads (Configuration Files): A detailed threat model for malformed project configuration files (e.g., package.json, pom.xml) leading to sandbox escape, resource exhaustion, or unauthorized code execution. Detail countermeasures such as robust schema validation, input sanitization, and runtime integrity checks of configuration files.



